According to BBC, Uganda is home to around 1.3million refugees, which is the largest number of refugees in any country in Africa, and the third-largest in the world. Behind these huge numbers are conflicts in neighboring countries, the Democratic Republic of Congo and South Sudan, and more than 90% of Uganda’s refugees come from these two countries. But instead of fighting the tide of displacement, Uganda has become renowned for its welcoming refugee policies. BBC’s Ashley John-Baptiste met some of the refugees trying to make a home for themselves in the north of the country. This story is part of a BBC News series, called “The Displaced” a selection of stories exploring the human impact of this movement, and how it is changing our world. Watch the documentary below: The post This BBC Documentary explores Uganda having the largest number of Refugees in Africa | WATCH appeared first on BellaNaija – Showcasing Africa to the world. Read today!. Source: Bella Naija